What is docker?
Docker is a containerization platform that allows us to package an application along with its dependencies into a container. This ensures that the application runs consistently across different environments like development, testing, and production. It solves issues like dependency conflicts and ‘works on my machine’ problems. Docker uses images to create containers, which are lightweight and isolated


what is docker image and container ?
Docker Image is a read-only template that contains the application code, dependencies, libraries, and configuration required to run an application.

A Docker Container is a running instance of that image. It is a lightweight, isolated environment where the application actually executes.

In simple terms, an image is like a blueprint, and a container is the actual running application created from that blueprint.


what is Dockerfile?
A Dockerfile is a text file that contains a set of instructions to build a Docker image. It defines the base image, application code, dependencies, and commands required to run the application.”

Common Instructions:
FROM → specifies base image
WORKDIR → sets working directory
COPY / ADD → copies files into container
RUN → installs dependencies
CMD / ENTRYPOINT → defines how the container runs
🎯 Clean Example (Very Powerful in Interview)
FROM node:18
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN npm install
CMD ["npm", "start"]


what is cmd and entrypoint in dockerfile?
“CMD is used to provide a default command that runs when a container starts, and it can be overridden at runtime.

ENTRYPOINT, on the other hand, defines the main command of the container and is usually not overridden. It ensures the container always runs a specific executable.”

🎯 Best Way to Explain (Impress interviewer)

👉 Example:

FROM ubuntu
CMD ["echo", "Hello"]

Run:

docker run image-name

👉 Output: Hello

Override:

docker run image-name echo "Hi"

👉 Output: Hi

ENTRYPOINT Example:
FROM ubuntu
ENTRYPOINT ["echo"]

Run:

docker run image-name Hello

👉 Output: Hello

👉 Here, echo is fixed — only arguments change.


The main difference between Docker and Virtual Machines is in their architecture.

Docker uses containerization, where containers share the host operating system kernel, making them lightweight and fast.

Virtual Machines use a hypervisor and include a full guest operating system, which makes them heavier and slower to start.

In short, Docker containers are lightweight and efficient, while VMs provide full isolation but consume more resources.

| Feature      | Docker         | Virtual Machine |
| ------------ | -------------- | --------------- |
| OS           | Shares host OS | Separate OS     |
| Size         | Lightweight    | Heavy           |
| Startup Time | Seconds        | Minutes         |
| Performance  | Faster         | Slower          |

what is docker Volumes ?
Docker volumes are used for persistent data storage. By default, any data inside a container is lost when the container is removed. Volumes store data outside the container, so it remains safe even if the container stops or is deleted.

docker run -v myvolume:/data mysql



How does Docker networking work? How do containers communicate with each other?

Docker networking allows containers to communicate with each other using virtual networks. By default, Docker creates a bridge network where containers can talk using IP addresses or container names.

In Docker Compose, all services are connected to a common network, and containers can communicate using service names as hostnames. Docker also provides built-in DNS to resolve these names automatically


